      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 65-year-old man, bedridden in the ICU with a urinary catheter, develops a catheter-associated urinary tract infection (CAUTI) and ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP). Considering the common pathogens and resistance patterns in India, which of the following is the most appropriate choice of antibiotic for this patient?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5530507",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35730,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Beta lactams/beta lactamase inhibitors</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></span></strong></span></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In bedridden patients in ICU, cause of catheter associated -<strong>UTI and VAP are usually the multidrug resistant gram negative bacilli</strong>. Therefore, <strong>empirically Beta lactams/beta lactamase inhibitors</strong> such as <strong>Piperacillin-tazobactam</strong> or <strong>Cefoperazone-sulbactam</strong> can be <strong>started which can be tailored later based on culture/sensitivity report.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In <strong>ICU settings for patients with Catheter-Associated Urinary Tract Infections</strong> (CAUTI) and <strong>Ventilator-Associated Pneumonia</strong> (VAP), <strong>beta-lactams</strong> combined with <strong>beta-lactamase inhibitors</strong> are often the preferred choice. This <strong>combination effectively addresses a wide range of bacteria</strong>, and the addition of <strong>beta-lactamase inhibitors</strong> helps <strong>counteract resistance in certain bacterial strains.</strong> This is particularly relevant in the context of the common pathogens and resistance patterns observed in India.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Option A.</strong> <strong>Amoxicillin -</strong> <strong>Not broad enough</strong> for the typical pathogens associated with CAUTI and VAP, especially in an ICU setting.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Third-generation cephalosporin</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - While useful, they <strong>may not cover all the potential pathogens</strong>, especially those producing beta-lactamase.</span></span></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Second-generation cephalosporin</strong> - Generally <strong>less effective than third-generation cephalosporins</strong> and beta lactams/beta lactamase inhibitors for these infections.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Beta lactams/beta lactamase inhibitors</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> are often the <strong>choice in ICU settings for patients with CAUTI and VAP</strong>, especially when considering the <strong>common pathogens and resistance patterns in India</strong>. These antibiotics are effective against a wide range of bacteria and the addition of beta-lactamase inhibitors helps overcome resistance in certain bacteria.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Apurba Sastry&rsquo;s Essentials of Med.Microbiology 2/e p644,665</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
